    "faq": [
      {
        "question": "What is Semantic Scholar and why do I need cookies?",
        "answer": "Semantic Scholar is an academic search engine. The skill uses browser cookies to access your private library and research feed. Cookies are stored locally and never sent to third parties."
      },
      {
        "question": "How do I get my Semantic Scholar cookies?",
        "answer": "Open Semantic Scholar in your browser, open Developer Tools (F12), go to the Network tab, find a request, right-click and select 'Copy as cURL'. Then paste it when the skill asks for it."
      },
      {
        "question": "Is my data safe when using this skill?",
        "answer": "Yes. Cookies are stored in a local file under ~/.auth/. All network requests go to semanticscholar.org. No data is sent to any third-party server."
      },
      {
        "question": "Can I use this skill without a Semantic Scholar account?",
        "answer": "No. You need an active Semantic Scholar account with a valid session to access library folders and research feeds. The public Graph API endpoints work without cookies."
      },
      {
        "question": "How do I know if my cookies are expired?",
        "answer": "Run the cookie-summary command. It shows cookie expiry status and which required cookies (sid, s2) are present. Stale cookies cause 401 errors on API calls."
      },
      {
        "question": "Can I add papers to multiple folders at once?",
        "answer": "Yes. Use the folder-add command with multiple folder IDs separated by commas. Use --dry-run first to verify the operation before executing it."
      }
